# Backend C# — Critical Rules Summary

Full convention guides are in `docs/conventions/backend/`. Read the relevant file before editing a layer. This file is a quick reference only.

## The Five Critical Rules

### 1. Sealed by Default

All classes not designed for inheritance MUST be declared `sealed`. This includes all aggregates, entities, value objects, handlers, validators, endpoints, and EF Core configuration classes.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class CreatePostCommandHandler : ICommandHandler<CreatePostCommand> { }

// BAD:
class CreatePostCommandHandler : ICommandHandler<CreatePostCommand> { }
```

### 2. No Controllers — IEndpoint Only

Never create a class that inherits from `ControllerBase` or `Controller`. All HTTP endpoints MUST implement `IEndpoint`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class CreatePostEndpoint : IEndpoint
{
    public void MapEndpoint(IEndpointRouteBuilder app) { ... }
}

// BAD:
[ApiController]
[Route("api/posts")]
class PostsController : ControllerBase { }
```

### 3. No Aggregate Loading in Query Handlers

Query handlers MUST inject a read store interface (`IXxxReadStore`), not a domain repository. Never call a repository inside a query handler.

```csharp
// GOOD:
sealed class GetPostByIdQueryHandler(IPostReadStore readStore)
    : IQueryHandler<GetPostByIdQuery, PostResult> { }

// BAD:
sealed class GetPostByIdQueryHandler(IPostRepository repository)
    : IQueryHandler<GetPostByIdQuery, PostResult> { }
```

### 4. Correct Exception Hierarchy

See `docs/conventions/backend/06-exception-hierarchy.md` for the full contract.

- Validators throw `ApplicationValidationException` subclasses.
- Repositories throw `AggregateNotFoundException` subclasses.
- Aggregate methods throw `DomainException` subclasses.
- NEVER throw `InvalidOperationException`, `ArgumentException`, or `ArgumentNullException` in domain or application code.

### 5. CancellationToken on All Async Methods

Every `async` method and every method that calls an `async` method MUST accept and propagate a `CancellationToken`.

```csharp
// GOOD:
Task<PostResult> HandleAsync(GetPostByIdQuery query, CancellationToken cancellationToken);

// BAD:
Task<PostResult> HandleAsync(GetPostByIdQuery query);
```
